\description{
\code{kruskal_wallis()} compares three or more groups when your data isn't
normally distributed or when you have ordinal data (like ratings or rankings).
It's the non-parametric alternative to one-way ANOVA.

Think of it as:
\itemize{
\item An extension of the Mann-Whitney test for more than two groups
\item A robust way to compare groups that works with any data shape
\item Perfect for Likert scales, rankings, or skewed distributions
}

The test tells you:
\itemize{
\item Whether at least one group is different from the others
\item How strong the overall group effect is (effect size)
\item Which groups tend to have higher or lower values (via mean ranks)
}
}
\details{
\subsection{Understanding the Results}{

\strong{P-value}: If p < 0.05, at least one group is significantly different
\itemize{
\item p < 0.001: Very strong evidence of group differences
\item p < 0.01: Strong evidence of group differences
\item p < 0.05: Moderate evidence of group differences
\item p > 0.05: No significant group differences found
}

\strong{Effect Size Eta-squared} (How much do groups matter?):
\itemize{
\item < 0.01: Negligible effect
\item 0.01-0.06: Small effect
\item 0.06-0.14: Medium effect
\item 0.14 or higher: Large effect
}

\strong{Mean Ranks}:
\itemize{
\item Higher mean rank = group tends to have higher values
\item Lower mean rank = group tends to have lower values
\item Compare mean ranks to see the pattern of group differences
}
}

\subsection{When to Use This}{

Use Kruskal-Wallis test when:
\itemize{
\item Your data is not normally distributed (skewed, outliers)
\item You have ordinal data (rankings, Likert scales)
\item Sample sizes are small or very unequal across groups
\item You want a robust alternative to one-way ANOVA
\item You're comparing satisfaction ratings, income, or other skewed variables
}
}

\subsection{What Comes Next?}{

If the Kruskal-Wallis test is significant:
\enumerate{
\item Look at mean ranks to see the pattern
\item Use pairwise Mann-Whitney tests with Bonferroni correction to find
which specific groups differ
\item Consider effect sizes to judge practical importance
}
}

\subsection{Relationship to Other Tests}{
\itemize{
\item For 2 groups: Use \code{\link{mann_whitney}()} instead
\item For normally distributed data: Use \code{\link{oneway_anova}()} instead
\item For repeated measures (same subjects): Use \code{friedman_test()} instead
}
}
